# Node SDK Nullability Convention

When designing or updating `feeefjs` request/update types:

- In the Node.js/TypeScript SDK, use `undefined` to mean "do not send this field".
- Use `null` only when the API should explicitly clear a nullable field.
- Do not add Dart-style `setToNull` helpers to the Node.js SDK unless there is a backend requirement that cannot be expressed with normal JS `undefined`/`null` semantics.

Examples:

```typescript
// GOOD: leave unchanged
await ff.imagePromptTemplates.update({
  id: templateId,
  data: {
    name: 'Updated name',
    description: undefined,
  },
})

// GOOD: explicitly clear nullable field
await ff.imagePromptTemplates.update({
  id: templateId,
  data: {
    previewImageUrl: null,
  },
})

// BAD: adding setToNull just because Dart uses it
await ff.imagePromptTemplates.update({
  id: templateId,
  data: {
    setToNull: ['previewImageUrl'],
  },
})
```
